          "body": "Verse 15 is the chapter's theological floor. Paul describes his conversion not primarily as his decision to follow Christ but as God's prior action: God 'set me apart from my mother's womb and called me through His grace.' The vocabulary deliberately echoes Jeremiah 1:5 ('before I formed you in the womb I knew you') and Isaiah 49:1 ('the LORD called Me from the womb'). Paul places himself in the prophetic call-narrative tradition. The implications are striking: even Saul the persecutor was already, in God's sovereign reckoning, the apostle to the Gentiles. The Damascus road did not change God's mind about Paul; it revealed God's mind to Paul. Reformed and classical Arminian commentators agree on the divine priority of this calling, though they parse the relationship of grace and human response differently — both readings honor Paul's own emphasis that grace, not works or merit, is the engine."
